[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Types of interoperability include **syntactic interoperability**, where two systems can communicate with each other, and cross-domain interoperability, where multiple organizations work together and exchange information.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] If two or more systems use common data formats and communication protocols, then they are capable of communicating with each other, and they exhibit *syntactic interoperability*.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] XML and SQL are examples of common data formats and protocols.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Low-level data formats also contribute to syntactic interoperability, ensuring that alphabetical characters are stored in the same ASCII or a Unicode format in all the communicating systems.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Beyond the ability of two or more computer systems to exchange information, semantic interoperability is the ability to automatically interpret the information exchanged meaningfully and accurately in order to produce useful results as defined by the end users of both systems.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] To achieve semantic interoperability, both sides must refer to a common information exchange reference model.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] The content of the information exchange requests are unambiguously defined: what is sent is the same as what is understood.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Cross-domain interoperability involves multiple social, organizational, political, legal entities working together for a common interest or information exchange.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Interoperability implies exchanges between a range of products, or similar products from several different vendors, or even between past and future revisions of the same product.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Interoperability may be developed *post-facto*, as a special measure between two products, while excluding the rest, by using open standards.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] When a vendor is forced to adapt its system to a dominant system that is not based on open standards, it is compatibility, not interoperability.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Open standards rely on a broadly consultative and inclusive group, including representatives from vendors, academics and others holding a stake in the development that discusses and debates the technical and economic merits, demerits and feasibility of a proposed common protocol.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] After the doubts and reservations of all members are addressed, the resulting common document is endorsed as a *common standard*.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] This document may be subsequently released to the public, and henceforth becomes an *open standard*.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] It is usually published and is available freely or at a nominal cost to any and all comers, with *no further encumbrances*.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] The vendors' products compete on the quality of their implementation, user interface, ease of use, performance, price, and a host of other factors, while keeping the customer's data intact and transferable even if they choose to switch to another competing product for business reasons.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] However, while "open" is a necessary condition for an interoperabilty standard, it is not a sufficient condition.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] For example, the standard-setting processes for the Fortran, C, and C++ languages are open, with a broadly-inclusive consultative group.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] But the resulting standards are not interoperability standards.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] The data itself may be encumbered, e.g., by patents or pricing, leading to a dependence of all competing solutions on the original vendor, and possibly leading to a revenue stream from the competitors' customers back to the original vendor.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] This revenue stream is the result of the original product's market dominance and not a result of any innate superiority.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Alternatively, it can be argued that even open processes are subject to the weight of past implementations and imperfect past designs and that the power of the dominant vendor to unilaterally correct or improve the system and impose the changes to all users facilitates innovation.
[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] Lack of an open standard can also become problematic for the customers, as in the case of the original vendor's inability to fix a certain problem that is an artifact of technical limitations in the original product.
