[src:multi-cloud/interoperability] The National Institute of Standards and Technology serves as an agency for measurement standards.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] When effectively implemented, multicloud solutions can enhance architectural resilience, reduce dependence on a single vendor, and improve flexibility by leveraging services from different providers.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] However, multicloud strategies also present challenges, including increased operational complexity, security risks, higher costs, and integration difficulties.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] According to the 2024 State of the Cloud Report by Flexera, multi-cloud adoption has continued to rise in 2024.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] Enterprises increasingly silo applications into specific clouds and select best-fit services.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] Key use cases include data analysis in separate clouds and cross-cloud disaster recovery.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] There are several advantages to using a multicloud approach, including the ability to negotiate better pricing with cloud providers, the ability to quickly switch to another provider if needed, and the ability to avoid vendor lock-in.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] Multicloud can also be a good way to hedge against the risks of obsolescence, as it allows you to rely on multiple vendors and open standards, which can prolong the life of your systems.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] Various issues and challenges also present themselves in a multicloud environment.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] Security and governance is more complicated, and more "moving parts" may create resiliency issues.
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] Multicloud differs from hybrid cloud in that it refers to multiple cloud services from different vendors rather than multiple deployment modes (on-premises hardware, and public and private, cloud hosting).
[src:multi-cloud/multicloud] However, when considering a broad definition of multi-cloud, hybrid cloud can still be regarded as a special form of multi-cloud.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] In economics, **vendor lock-in**, also known as **proprietary lock-in** or **customer lock‑in**, makes a customer dependent on a vendor for products, unable to use another vendor without substantial switching costs.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] The use of open standards and alternative options makes systems tolerant of change, so that decisions can be postponed until more information is available or unforeseen events are addressed.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Vendor lock-in does the opposite: it makes it difficult to move from one solution to another.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Lock-in costs that create barriers to market entry may result in antitrust action against a monopoly.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Whether a single vendor controls the market for the method or technology being locked in to.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Distinguishes between being locked to the mere technology, or specifically the vendor of it.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] This class of lock-in is potentially technologically hard to overcome if the monopoly is held up by barriers to market that are nontrivial to circumvent, such as patents, secrecy, cryptography or other technical hindrances.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Whether individuals are locked in collectively, in part through each other.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] the locally dominant choice, as if by friction between individuals.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] This class of lock-in is potentially inescapable to rational individuals not otherwise motivated, by creating a prisoner's dilemma—if the cost to resist is greater than the cost of joining, then the locally optimal choice is to join—a barrier that takes cooperation to overcome.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Technology lock-in, as defined, is strictly of the collective kind.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] However, the personal variant is also a possible permutation of the variations shown in the table, but with no monopoly and no collectivity, it would be expected to be the weakest lock-in.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] There exist lock-in situations that are both monopolistic and collective.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Having the worst of two worlds, these can be very hard to escape E.g, the cost to resist incurs some level of isolation from the (dominating technology in) society, which can be socially costly, yet direct competition with the dominant vendor is hindered by compatibility.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Microsoft's application software also exhibits lock-in through the use of proprietary file formats.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Microsoft Outlook uses a proprietary, publicly undocumented datastore format.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] In 2007 Microsoft introduced a new format MS-OOXML for their office suite; However Microsoft do not claim to support this as their default file format, instead stating that the default is an "XML-based" file format.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Additionally, Microsoft introduced a new undocumented line break algorithm for Microsoft Word 2013 onwards, this was after ODF and OOXML standardization.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] The secret algorithm/s were reverse engineered 13 years later with financial support from the European Commission, benefiting competing office suites LibreOffice, Collabora Online, and others.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Prior to March 2009, digital music files with digital rights management (DRM) were available for purchase from the iTunes Store, encoded in a proprietary derivative of the AAC format that used Apple's FairPlay DRM system.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] These files are compatible only with Apple's iTunes media player software on Macs and Windows, their iPod portable digital music players, iPhone smartphones, iPad tablet computers, and the Motorola ROKR E1 and SLVR mobile phones.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] As a result, that music was locked into this ecosystem and available for portable use only through the purchase of one of the above devices, or by burning to CD and optionally re-ripping to a DRM-free format such as MP3 or WAV.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] In January 2005, an iPod purchaser named Thomas Slattery filed a suit against Apple for the "unlawful bundling" of their iTunes Music Store and iPod device.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] At the time, Apple was stated to have an 80% market share of digital music sales and a 90% share of sales of new music players, which he claimed allowed Apple to horizontally leverage its dominant positions in both markets to lock consumers into its complementary offerings.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] District Judge James Ware approved *Slattery v.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Apple Computer Inc.* to proceed with monopoly charges against Apple in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] On June 7, 2006, the Norwegian Consumer Council stated that Apple's iTunes Music Store violates Norwegian law.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] The contract conditions were vague and "clearly unbalanced to disfavor the customer".
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] The retroactive changes to the DRM conditions and the incompatibility with other music players are the major points of concern.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] In an earlier letter to Apple, consumer ombudsman Bjørn Erik Thon complained that iTunes' DRM mechanism was a lock-in to Apple's music players, and argued that this was a conflict with consumer rights that he doubted would be defendable by Norwegian copyright law.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] As of 29 May 2007, tracks on the EMI label became available in a DRM-free format called iTunes Plus.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] These files are unprotected and are encoded in the AAC format at 256 kilobits per second, twice the bitrate of standard tracks bought through the service. iTunes accounts can be set to display either standard or iTunes Plus formats for tracks where both formats exist.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] These files can be used with any player that supports the AAC file format and are not locked to Apple hardware.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] They can be converted to MP format if desired.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] As of January 6, 2009, all four big music studios (Warner Bros., Sony BMG, Universal, and EMI) have signed up to remove the DRM from their tracks, at no extra cost.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] However, Apple charges consumers to have previously purchased DRM music restrictions removed.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Although Google has stated its position in favor of interoperability, the company has taken steps away from open protocols replacing open standard Google Talk by proprietary protocol Google Hangouts.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Also, Google's Data Liberation Front has been inactive on Twitter since 2013 and its official website, www.dataliberation.org, now redirects to a page on Google's FAQs, leading users to believe the project has been closed.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Google's mobile operating system Android is open source; however, the operating system that comes with the phones that most people actually purchase in a store is more often than not shipped with many of Google's proprietary applications that promote users to use only Google services.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Because cloud computing is still relatively new, standards are still being developed.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Many cloud platforms and services are proprietary, meaning that they are built on the specific standards, tools and protocols developed by a particular vendor for its particular cloud offering.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] This can make migrating off a proprietary cloud platform prohibitively complicated and expensive.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Heterogeneous cloud computing is described as a type of cloud environment that prevents vendor lock-in, and aligns with enterprise data centers that are operating hybrid cloud models.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] The absence of vendor lock-in lets cloud administrators select their choice of hypervisors for specific tasks, or to deploy virtualized infrastructures to other enterprises without the need to consider the flavor of hypervisor in the other enterprise.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] A heterogeneous cloud is considered one that includes on-premises private clouds, public clouds and software-as-a-service clouds.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Heterogeneous clouds can work with environments that are not virtualized, such as traditional data centers.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Heterogeneous clouds also allow for the use of piece parts, such as hypervisors, servers, and storage, from multiple vendors.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Cloud piece parts, such as cloud storage systems, offer APIs but they are often incompatible with each other.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] The result is complicated migration between backends, and makes it difficult to integrate data spread across various locations.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] This has been described as a problem of vendor lock-in.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] The solution to this is for clouds to adopt common standards.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Heterogeneous cloud computing differs from homogeneous clouds, which have been described as those using consistent building blocks supplied by a single vendor.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Intel General Manager of high-density computing, Jason Waxman, is quoted as saying that a homogeneous system of 15,000 servers would cost $6 million more in capital expenditure and use 1 megawatt of power.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Oracle Corporation executives in 2007 told of how Boeing got into an argument with Larry Ellison at a contract meeting, after the latter acknowledged that Oracle Database version 7 had 11,000 bugs and insulted the Boeing 777.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] Boeing refused to sign the contract, and was also an IBM customer so had an alternative.
[src:multi-cloud/vendor-lock-in] The company was so dependent on Oracle, however, that it resumed negotiations and signed the contract.
